al crises of legitimacy’, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">International Politics </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">44 (2007) p.164 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt"> See James Pattison, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">RtoP</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt"> and Responsibility while Protecting’  http://www.du.edu/korbel/hrhw/roundtable/2012/panel-b/10-2012/pattison-2012a.html</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt"> The Foreign Secretary stated that an intervention could be lawful without UN approval on 26 August.  See Nicholas Watt, ‘Syria: UK and US move closer to intervention’, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The Guardian </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">26 August 2013 http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/aug/26/syria-uk-us-intervention. However, a 3rd September </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">Ipsos</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt"> Mori poll showed 71% opposed taking military action without UN approval.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn20"></a><a href="#_ftnref20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt"> Michael Clarke, ‘No 10’s shifty and rushed battle plan’, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sunday Times </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt">1 September 2013, p.14.  On the legal argument, Robert Booth, ‘Syria: legal doubt cast on British government's case’, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:10pt; font-st